 from word distribution in a text: Phrases that are linked to a local context are retained, while phrases that have no such links are dropped.
    Another difference between these two methods is the extensive use of knowledge resources in the latter.
    For example, a lexicon is used to identify which components of the sentence are obligatory to keep it grammatically correct.
    The corpus in this approach is used to estimate the degree to which a fragment is extraneous and can be omitted from a summary.
    A phrase is removed only if it is not grammatically obligatory, is not linked to a local context, and has a reasonable probability of being removed by humans.
    In addition to reducing the original sentences, Jing and McKeown (2000) use a number of manually compiled rules to aggregate reduced sentences; for example, reduced clauses might be conjoined with and.
